Problem 1

The Washington Post has gathered data on homicides in 50 large U.S. cities and made the data available through a GitHub repository here. You can read their accompanying article here.

Describe the raw data. Create a city_state variable (e.g. “Baltimore, MD”) and then summarize within cities to obtain the total number of homicides and the number of unsolved homicides (those for which the disposition is “Closed without arrest” or “Open/No arrest”).

homicide = 
  read.csv("./homicide-data.csv")|>
  mutate(city_state = paste(city, state, sep = ", "))

homicide_data =
  homicide |>
  group_by (city) |>
  summarize(total_homicides=n(),
            unsolved_homicides=sum(disposition %in% c("Closed without arrest","Closed by arrest")))

  homicide |>
  filter(city == "Baltimore", state == "MD")

Now run prop.test for each of the cities in your dataset, and extract both the proportion of unsolved homicides and the confidence interval for each. Do this within a “tidy” pipeline, making use of purrr::map, purrr::map2, list columns and unnest as necessary to create a tidy dataframe with estimated proportions and CIs for each city.

# Create a summary dataframe with counts of unsolved and total homicides by city
city_summary <- homicide %>%
  group_by(city, state) %>%
  summarise(
    unsolved_homicides = sum(disposition %in% c("Closed without arrest", "Open/No arrest")),
    total_homicides = n(),
    .groups = "drop"
  )

# Use purrr to apply prop.test to each city and tidy the results
tidy_prop_test_results <- city_summary %>%
  mutate(
    prop_test = map2(unsolved_homicides, total_homicides, ~prop.test(.x, .y)),
    tidy_results = map(prop_test, broom::tidy)
  ) %>%
  select(city, state, tidy_results) %>%
  unnest(tidy_results)
## Warning: There was 1 warning in `mutate()`.

tidy_proportions_ci <- tidy_prop_test_results %>%
  select(city, state, estimate, conf.low, conf.high)

Create a plot that shows the estimates and CIs for each city – check out geom_errorbar for a way to add error bars based on the upper and lower limits. Organize cities according to the proportion of unsolved homicides.

tidy_proportions_ci <- tidy_proportions_ci %>%
  arrange(desc(estimate))
plot <- ggplot(tidy_proportions_ci, aes(x = reorder(city, estimate), y = estimate)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = conf.low, ymax = conf.high), width = 0.2) +
  coord_flip() +  # Flip the axes to make the plot horizontal
  labs(x = "City", y = "Proportion of Unsolved Homicides", title = "Proportion of Unsolved Homicides by City") +
  theme_minimal()

Problem 2

This zip file contains data from a longitudinal study that included a control arm and an experimental arm. Data for each participant is included in a separate file, and file names include the subject ID and arm. Create a tidy dataframe containing data from all participants, including the subject ID, arm, and observations over time: - Start with a dataframe containing all file names; the list.files function will help. - Iterate over file names and read in data for each subject using purrr::map and saving the result as a new variable in the dataframe. - Tidy the result; manipulate file names to include control arm and subject ID, make sure weekly observations are “tidy”, and do any other tidying that’s necessary.

Firstly, we load in the data files by using list.files() with input of path, pattern, and full.names. Then we will use map_dfrto map the function of read_csv() that load in several csv documents with repetition. We should also use mutate() to help combine the csv documents together with corresponded subject_id and control_arm. By using str_extract() function, we can use regex to extract the according values we want. After getting the combined dataframe, we need to clean it by using pivot_longer() to collect the week 1 to week 8 together into one week column. Then for later graphing, we need to recode the week_1 to 1 by using mutate() and recode().

file_names = 
  list.files(path = './data', 
             pattern = '.csv',
             full.names = TRUE)

  )

Problem 3

When designing an experiment or analysis, a common question is whether it is likely that a true effect will be detected – put differently, whether a false null hypothesis will be rejected. The probability that a false null hypothesis is rejected is referred to as power, and it depends on several factors, including: the sample size; the effect size; and the error variance. In this problem, you will conduct a simulation to explore power in a one-sample t-test.

First set the following design elements:

Fix n=30 Fix σ=5 Set μ=0 . Generate 5000 datasets from the model

x∼Normal[μ,σ]

For each dataset, save μ̂ and the p-value arising from a test of H:μ=0 using α=0.05 . Hint: to obtain the estimate and p-value, use broom::tidy to clean the output of t.test.

We will do a simulation function by using function() and setting sigma = 5, sample_size = 30. Then we will add t test with t.test() with broom::tidy to tidy the test results. Then we use a for loop to run the simulaiton 5000 times with input of mu = 0.

set.seed(12345)

simulation = function(mu, sigma = 5, sample_size = 30) {

  data = rnorm(n = sample_size, mean = mu, sd = sigma)
  
  sim_data = tibble(
  mu_hat = mean(data),
  sigma_hat = sd(data)
  
  )

test = 
  t.test(data, alternative = 'two.sided', conf.level = 0.95) |>
  broom::tidy()

}

output = vector("list", 5000)

for (i in 1:5000) {
  output[[i]] = simulation(mu = 0)
}

sim_datasets = bind_rows(output)

Repeat the above for μ={1,2,3,4,5,6}

After we create the simulation function, we can use expand_grid for repetition by specifying input values of 0 to 6 and iteration times of 5000. Then we can use mutate() to use map() to map the function of simulation on the input of mu. Then we use unnest() to get our new repetition data.

# Repeat the above simulation for u ={1,2,3,4,5,6}
repetition =
  expand_grid(
    mu = c(0,1,2,3,4,5,6),
    iter = 1:5000
  ) |>
  mutate(
    estimate_df = map(mu, ~simulation(.x))
  ) |>
  unnest(estimate_df)

Make a plot showing the proportion of times the null was rejected (the power of the test) on the y axis and the true value of μ on the x axis. Describe the association between effect size and power.

To make a power plot, we need to clean the repetition by using group_by() and summarise() to get our x and y and then use ggplot() to plot the graph. Then we add geom_line() and geom_point() and geom_smooth() for visualizations then finally add title and axis names with labs().

power_df = 
  repetition |>
  group_by(mu) |>
  summarise(
    p_value = mean(p.value < 0.05),
    sample_size = n(),
    proportion = p_value/sample_size
  )
power_df

Make a second plot (or overlay on the first) the average estimate of μ̂ only in samples for which the null was rejected on the y axis and the true value of μ on the x axis.

average_null_df =

Is the sample average of μ̂ across tests for which the null is rejected approximately equal to the true value of μ? Why or why not?

No, he average estimates plot shows the average estimate of μ is approximately equal to the true value of μ. However, the average estimate of μ̂ only in samples for which the null was rejected have some difference with the true value ofu.since,wWhen the true value of mu is closer to the null hypothesis, the test may not have enough power to consistently reject the null hypothesis, leading to a biased sample of estimates where the null is rejected. As the true value of mu increases, the power of the test also increases, making it more likely to reject the null hypothesis when it is false.
